glam::BVec4::any.documentation: Returns true if any of the elements are true, false otherwise.

glam::BVec4::bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 4 bits set from the elements of `self`.
 A true element results in a `1` bit and a false element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.

glam::BVec4::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector mask from a bool array.

glam::BVec4::set.documentation:
Sets the element at `index`.
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::BVec4::splat.documentation: Creates a vector mask with all elements set to `v`.

glam::BVec4::test.documentation:
Tests the value at `index`.
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::BVec4A::all.documentation: Returns true if all the elements are true, false otherwise.

glam::BVec4A::any.documentation: Returns true if any of the elements are true, false otherwise.

glam::BVec4A::bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 4 bits set from the elements of `self`.
 A true element results in a `1` bit and a false element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.

glam::BVec4A::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector mask from a bool array.

glam::BVec4A::set.documentation:
Sets the element at `index`.
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::BVec4A::splat.documentation: Creates a vector mask with all elements set to `v`.

glam::BVec4A::test.documentation:
Tests the value at `index`.
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::DAffine2::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two 3x4 matrices contain similar elements. It works
 best when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DAffine2::from_angle.documentation: Creates an affine transform from the given rotation `angle`.

glam::DAffine2::from_angle_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from the given 2D rotation `angle` (in radians) and
 `translation`.
 Equivalent to `DAffine2::from_translation(translation) * DAffine2::from_angle(angle)`

glam::DAffine2::from_cols.documentation: Creates an affine transform from three column vectors.

glam::DAffine2::from_mat2.documentation: Creates an affine transform from a 2x2 matrix (expressing scale, shear and rotation)

glam::DAffine2::from_mat2_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from a 2x2 matrix (expressing scale, shear and rotation) and a
 translation vector.
 Equivalent to
 `DAffine2::from_translation(translation) * DAffine2::from_mat2(mat2)`

glam::DAffine2::from_mat3.documentation: The given `DMat3` must be an affine transform,

glam::DAffine2::from_scale.documentation:
Creates an affine transform that changes scale.
 Note that if any scale is zero the transform will be non-invertible.

glam::DAffine2::from_scale_angle_transla.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from the given 2D `scale`, rotation `angle` (in radians) and
 `translation`.
 Equivalent to `DAffine2::from_translation(translation) *
 DAffine2::from_angle(angle) * DAffine2::from_scale(scale)`

glam::DAffine2::from_translation.documentation: Creates an affine transformation from the given 2D `translation`.

glam::DAffine2::inverse.documentation:
Return the inverse of this transform.
 Note that if the transform is not invertible the result will be invalid.

glam::DAffine2::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return
 `false`.

glam::DAffine2::to_cols_array.documentation: Creates a `[f64; 6]` array storing data in column major order.

glam::DAffine2::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f64; 2]; 3]` 2D array storing data in
 column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DAffine2::transform_point2.documentation: Transforms the given 2D point, applying shear, scale, rotation and translation.

glam::DAffine2::transform_vector2.documentation:
Transforms the given 2D vector, applying shear, scale and rotation (but NOT
 translation).
 To also apply translation, use [`Self::transform_point2()`] instead.

glam::DAffine3::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two 3x4 matrices contain similar elements. It works
 best when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DAffine3::from_axis_angle.documentation:
Creates an affine transform containing a 3D rotation around a normalized
 rotation `axis` of `angle` (in radians).

glam::DAffine3::from_cols.documentation: Creates an affine transform from three column vectors.

glam::DAffine3::from_mat3.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from a 3x3 matrix (expressing scale, shear and
 rotation)

glam::DAffine3::from_mat3_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from a 3x3 matrix (expressing scale, shear and rotation)
 and a translation vector.
 Equivalent to `DAffine3::from_translation(translation) * DAffine3::from_mat3(mat3)`

glam::DAffine3::from_mat4.documentation:
The given `DMat4` must be an affine transform,
 i.e. contain no perspective transform.

glam::DAffine3::from_quat.documentation: Creates an affine transform from the given `rotation` quaternion.

glam::DAffine3::from_rotation_translatio.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from the given 3D `rotation` and `translation`.
 Equivalent to `DAffine3::from_translation(translation) * DAffine3::from_quat(rotation)`

glam::DAffine3::from_rotation_x.documentation:
Creates an affine transform containing a 3D rotation around the x axis of
 `angle` (in radians).

glam::DAffine3::from_rotation_y.documentation:
Creates an affine transform containing a 3D rotation around the y axis of
 `angle` (in radians).

glam::DAffine3::from_rotation_z.documentation:
Creates an affine transform containing a 3D rotation around the z axis of
 `angle` (in radians).

glam::DAffine3::from_scale.documentation:
Creates an affine transform that changes scale.
 Note that if any scale is zero the transform will be non-invertible.

glam::DAffine3::from_scale_rotation_tran.documentation:
Creates an affine transform from the given 3D `scale`, `rotation` and
 `translation`.
 Equivalent to `DAffine3::from_translation(translation) *
 DAffine3::from_quat(rotation) * DAffine3::from_scale(scale)`

glam::DAffine3::from_translation.documentation: Creates an affine transformation from the given 3D `translation`.

glam::DAffine3::inverse.documentation:
Return the inverse of this transform.
 Note that if the transform is not invertible the result will be invalid.

glam::DAffine3::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return
 `false`.

glam::DAffine3::look_at_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed view transform using a camera position, an up direction, and a focal
 point.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=forward`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `up` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DAffine3::look_at_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed view transform using a camera position, an up direction, and a focal
 point.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=back`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `up` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DAffine3::look_to_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed view transform using a camera position, an up direction, and a facing
 direction.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=forward`.

glam::DAffine3::look_to_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed view transform using a camera position, an up direction, and a facing
 direction.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=back`.

glam::DAffine3::to_cols_array.documentation: Creates a `[f64; 12]` array storing data in column major order.

glam::DAffine3::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f64; 3]; 4]` 3D array storing data in
 column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DAffine3::transform_point3.documentation: Transforms the given 3D points, applying shear, scale, rotation and translation.

glam::DAffine3::transform_vector3.documentation:
Transforms the given 3D vector, applying shear, scale and rotation (but NOT
 translation).
 To also apply translation, use [`Self::transform_point3()`] instead.

glam::DMat2::abs.documentation: Takes the absolute value of each element in `self`

glam::DMat2::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two matrices contain similar elements. It works best
 when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DMat2::col.documentation:
Returns the matrix column for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 1.

glam::DMat2::div_scalar.documentation: Divides a 2x2 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat2::from_angle.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix containing a rotation of `angle` (in radians).

glam::DMat2::from_cols.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix from two column vectors.

glam::DMat2::from_diagonal.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix with its diagonal set to `diagonal` and all other entries set to 0.

glam::DMat2::from_mat3.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix from a 3x3 matrix, discarding the 2nd row and column.

glam::DMat2::from_mat3_minor.documentation:
Creates a 2x2 matrix from the minor of the given 3x3 matrix, discarding the `i`th column
 and `j`th row.
 # Panics
 Panics if `i` or `j` is greater than 2.

glam::DMat2::from_scale_angle.documentation:
Creates a 2x2 matrix containing the combining non-uniform `scale` and rotation of
 `angle` (in radians).

glam::DMat2::inverse.documentation:
Returns the inverse of `self`.
 If the matrix is not invertible the returned matrix will be invalid.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the determinant of `self` is zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat2::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DMat2::mul_scalar.documentation: Multiplies a 2x2 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat2::row.documentation:
Returns the matrix row for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 1.

glam::DMat2::to_cols_array.documentation:
Creates a `[f64; 4]` array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat2::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f64; 2]; 2]` 2D array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat3::abs.documentation: Takes the absolute value of each element in `self`

glam::DMat3::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two matrices contain similar elements. It works best
 when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DMat3::col.documentation:
Returns the matrix column for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 2.

glam::DMat3::div_scalar.documentation: Divides a 3x3 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat3::from_angle.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 2D rotation `angle` (in
 radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 2D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].

glam::DMat3::from_axis_angle.documentation:
Creates a 3D rotation matrix from a normalized rotation `axis` and `angle` (in
 radians).
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::from_cols.documentation: Creates a 3x3 matrix from three column vectors.

glam::DMat3::from_diagonal.documentation: Creates a 3x3 matrix with its diagonal set to `diagonal` and all other entries set to 0.

glam::DMat3::from_euler.documentation:
Creates a 3D rotation matrix from the given euler rotation sequence and the angles (in
 radians).

glam::DMat3::from_mat2.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 2x2 matrix.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 2D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].

glam::DMat3::from_mat4.documentation: Creates a 3x3 matrix from a 4x4 matrix, discarding the 4th row and column.

glam::DMat3::from_mat4_minor.documentation:
Creates a 3x3 matrix from the minor of the given 4x4 matrix, discarding the `i`th column
 and `j`th row.
 # Panics
 Panics if `i` or `j` is greater than 3.

glam::DMat3::from_quat.documentation:
Creates a 3D rotation matrix from the given quaternion.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rotation` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::from_rotation_x.documentation: Creates a 3D rotation matrix from `angle` (in radians) around the x axis.

glam::DMat3::from_rotation_y.documentation: Creates a 3D rotation matrix from `angle` (in radians) around the y axis.

glam::DMat3::from_rotation_z.documentation: Creates a 3D rotation matrix from `angle` (in radians) around the z axis.

glam::DMat3::from_scale.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given non-uniform 2D `scale`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 2D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if all elements of `scale` are zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::from_scale_angle_translatio.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 2D `scale`, rotation `angle` (in
 radians) and `translation`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 2D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].

glam::DMat3::from_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 2D `translation`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 2D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].

glam::DMat3::inverse.documentation:
Returns the inverse of `self`.
 If the matrix is not invertible the returned matrix will be invalid.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the determinant of `self` is zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DMat3::mul_scalar.documentation: Multiplies a 3x3 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat3::row.documentation:
Returns the matrix row for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 2.

glam::DMat3::to_cols_array.documentation:
Creates a `[f64; 9]` array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat3::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f64; 3]; 3]` 3D array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat3::to_euler.documentation:
Extract Euler angles with the given Euler rotation order.
 Note if the input matrix contains scales, shears, or other non-rotation transformations then
 the resulting Euler angles will be ill-defined.
 # Panics
 Will panic if any input matrix column is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::transform_point2.documentation:
Transforms the given 2D vector as a point.
 This is the equivalent of multiplying `rhs` as a 3D vector where `z` is `1`.
 This method assumes that `self` contains a valid affine transform.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the 2nd row of `self` is not `(0, 0, 1)` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat3::transform_vector2.documentation:
Rotates the given 2D vector.
 This is the equivalent of multiplying `rhs` as a 3D vector where `z` is `0`.
 This method assumes that `self` contains a valid affine transform.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the 2nd row of `self` is not `(0, 0, 1)` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::abs.documentation: Takes the absolute value of each element in `self`

glam::DMat4::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two matrices contain similar elements. It works best
 when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DMat4::col.documentation:
Returns the matrix column for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::DMat4::div_scalar.documentation: Divides a 4x4 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat4::from_axis_angle.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix containing a 3D rotation around a normalized
 rotation `axis` of `angle` (in radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::from_cols.documentation: Creates a 4x4 matrix from four column vectors.

glam::DMat4::from_diagonal.documentation: Creates a 4x4 matrix with its diagonal set to `diagonal` and all other entries set to 0.

glam::DMat4::from_euler.documentation:
Creates a affine transformation matrix containing a rotation from the given euler
 rotation sequence and angles (in radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::from_mat3.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 3x3 linear transformation
 matrix.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::from_quat.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given `rotation` quaternion.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rotation` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::from_rotation_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 3D `translation`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rotation` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::from_rotation_x.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix containing a 3D rotation around the x axis of
 `angle` (in radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::from_rotation_y.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix containing a 3D rotation around the y axis of
 `angle` (in radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::from_rotation_z.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix containing a 3D rotation around the z axis of
 `angle` (in radians).
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::from_scale.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix containing the given 3D non-uniform `scale`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if all elements of `scale` are zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::from_scale_rotation_transla.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 3D `scale`, `rotation` and
 `translation`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rotation` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::from_translation.documentation:
Creates an affine transformation matrix from the given 3D `translation`.
 The resulting matrix can be used to transform 3D points and vectors. See
 [`Self::transform_point3()`] and [`Self::transform_vector3()`].

glam::DMat4::inverse.documentation:
Returns the inverse of `self`.
 If the matrix is not invertible the returned matrix will be invalid.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the determinant of `self` is zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DMat4::look_at_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed view matrix using a camera position, an up direction, and a focal
 point.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=forward`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `up` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::look_at_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed view matrix using a camera position, an up direction, and a focal
 point.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=back`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `up` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::look_to_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed view matrix using a camera position, an up direction, and a facing
 direction.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=forward`.

glam::DMat4::look_to_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed view matrix using a camera position, an up direction, and a facing
 direction.
 For a view coordinate system with `+X=right`, `+Y=up` and `+Z=back`.

glam::DMat4::mul_scalar.documentation: Multiplies a 4x4 matrix by a scalar.

glam::DMat4::orthographic_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed orthographic projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Useful to map a left-handed coordinate system to the normalized device coordinates that WebGPU/Direct3D/Metal expect.

glam::DMat4::orthographic_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed orthographic projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Useful to map a right-handed coordinate system to the normalized device coordinates that WebGPU/Direct3D/Metal expect.

glam::DMat4::orthographic_rh_gl.documentation:
Creates a right-handed orthographic projection matrix with `[-1,1]` depth
 range.  This is the same as the OpenGL `glOrtho` function in OpenGL.
 See
 <https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/gl2.1/xhtml/glOrtho.xml>
 Useful to map a right-handed coordinate system to the normalized device coordinates that OpenGL expects.

glam::DMat4::perspective_infinite_lh.documentation:
Creates an infinite left-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Like `perspective_lh`, but with an infinite value for `z_far`.
 The result is that points near `z_near` are mapped to depth `0`, and as they move towards infinity the depth approaches `1`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` or `z_far` are less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is
 enabled.

glam::DMat4::perspective_infinite_revers.documentation:
Creates an infinite reverse left-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Similar to `perspective_infinite_lh`, but maps `Z = z_near` to a depth of `1` and `Z = infinity` to a depth of `0`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` is less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

Creates an infinite reverse right-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Similar to `perspective_infinite_rh`, but maps `Z = z_near` to a depth of `1` and `Z = infinity` to a depth of `0`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` is less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::perspective_infinite_rh.documentation:
Creates an infinite right-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Like `perspective_rh`, but with an infinite value for `z_far`.
 The result is that points near `z_near` are mapped to depth `0`, and as they move towards infinity the depth approaches `1`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` or `z_far` are less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is
 enabled.

glam::DMat4::perspective_lh.documentation:
Creates a left-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Useful to map the standard left-handed coordinate system into what WebGPU/Metal/Direct3D expect.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` or `z_far` are less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is
 enabled.

glam::DMat4::perspective_rh.documentation:
Creates a right-handed perspective projection matrix with `[0,1]` depth range.
 Useful to map the standard right-handed coordinate system into what WebGPU/Metal/Direct3D expect.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `z_near` or `z_far` are less than or equal to zero when `glam_assert` is
 enabled.

glam::DMat4::perspective_rh_gl.documentation:
Creates a right-handed perspective projection matrix with `[-1,1]` depth range.
 Useful to map the standard right-handed coordinate system into what OpenGL expects.
 This is the same as the OpenGL `gluPerspective` function.
 See <https://www.khronos.org/registry/OpenGL-Refpages/gl2.1/xhtml/gluPerspective.xml>

glam::DMat4::project_point3.documentation:
Transforms the given 3D vector as a point, applying perspective correction.
 This is the equivalent of multiplying the 3D vector as a 4D vector where `w` is `1.0`.
 The perspective divide is performed meaning the resulting 3D vector is divided by `w`.
 This method assumes that `self` contains a projective transform.

glam::DMat4::row.documentation:
Returns the matrix row for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 3.

glam::DMat4::to_cols_array.documentation:
Creates a `[f64; 16]` array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat4::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f64; 4]; 4]` 4D array storing data in column major order.
 If you require data in row major order `transpose` the matrix first.

glam::DMat4::to_euler.documentation:
Extract Euler angles with the given Euler rotation order.
 Note if the upper 3x3 matrix contain scales, shears, or other non-rotation transformations
 then the resulting Euler angles will be ill-defined.
 # Panics
 Will panic if any column of the upper 3x3 rotation matrix is not normalized when
 `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::transform_point3.documentation:
Transforms the given 3D vector as a point.
 This is the equivalent of multiplying the 3D vector as a 4D vector where `w` is
 `1.0`.
 This method assumes that `self` contains a valid affine transform. It does not perform
 a perspective divide, if `self` contains a perspective transform, or if you are unsure,
 the [`Self::project_point3()`] method should be used instead.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the 3rd row of `self` is not `(0, 0, 0, 1)` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DMat4::transform_vector3.documentation:
Transforms the give 3D vector as a direction.
 This is the equivalent of multiplying the 3D vector as a 4D vector where `w` is
 `0.0`.
 This method assumes that `self` contains a valid affine transform.
 # Panics
 Will panic if the 3rd row of `self` is not `(0, 0, 0, 1)` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two quaternions contain similar elements. It works
 best when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DQuat::add.documentation:
Adds two quaternions.
 The sum is not guaranteed to be normalized.
 Note that addition is not the same as combining the rotations represented by the
 two quaternions! That corresponds to multiplication.

glam::DQuat::angle_between.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) for the minimal rotation
 for transforming this quaternion into another.
 Both quaternions must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `rhs` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::conjugate.documentation:
Returns the quaternion conjugate of `self`. For a unit quaternion the
 conjugate is also the inverse.

glam::DQuat::div.documentation:
Divides a quaternion by a scalar value.
 The quotient is not guaranteed to be normalized.

glam::DQuat::dot.documentation:
Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`. The dot product is
 equal to the cosine of the angle between two quaternion rotations.

glam::DQuat::from_affine3.documentation:
Creates a quaternion from a 3x3 rotation matrix inside a 3D affine transform.
 Note if the input affine matrix contain scales, shears, or other non-rotation
 transformations then the resulting quaternion will be ill-defined.
 # Panics
 Will panic if any input affine matrix column is not normalized when `glam_assert` is
 enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_array.documentation:
Creates a rotation quaternion from an array.
 # Preconditions
 This function does not check if the input is normalized, it is up to the user to
 provide normalized input or to normalized the resulting quaternion.

glam::DQuat::from_axis_angle.documentation:
Create a quaternion for a normalized rotation `axis` and `angle` (in radians).
 The axis must be a unit vector.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_euler.documentation: Creates a quaternion from the given Euler rotation sequence and the angles (in radians).

glam::DQuat::from_mat3.documentation:
Creates a quaternion from a 3x3 rotation matrix.
 Note if the input matrix contain scales, shears, or other non-rotation transformations then
 the resulting quaternion will be ill-defined.
 # Panics
 Will panic if any input matrix column is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_mat4.documentation:
Creates a quaternion from the upper 3x3 rotation matrix inside a homogeneous 4x4 matrix.
 Note if the upper 3x3 matrix contain scales, shears, or other non-rotation transformations
 then the resulting quaternion will be ill-defined.
 # Panics
 Will panic if any column of the upper 3x3 rotation matrix is not normalized when
 `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_arc.documentation:
Gets the minimal rotation for transforming `from` to `to`.  The rotation is in the
 plane spanned by the two vectors.  Will rotate at most 180 degrees.
 The inputs must be unit vectors.
 `from_rotation_arc(from, to) * from  to`.
 For near-singular cases (fromto and from-to) the current implementation
 is only accurate to about 0.001 (for `f32`).
 # Panics
 Will panic if `from` or `to` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_arc_2d.documentation:
Gets the minimal rotation for transforming `from` to `to`.  The resulting rotation is
 around the z axis. Will rotate at most 180 degrees.
 The inputs must be unit vectors.
 `from_rotation_arc_2d(from, to) * from  to`.
 For near-singular cases (fromto and from-to) the current implementation
 is only accurate to about 0.001 (for `f32`).
 # Panics
 Will panic if `from` or `to` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_arc_colinear.documentation:
Gets the minimal rotation for transforming `from` to either `to` or `-to`.  This means
 that the resulting quaternion will rotate `from` so that it is colinear with `to`.
 The rotation is in the plane spanned by the two vectors.  Will rotate at most 90
 degrees.
 The inputs must be unit vectors.
 `to.dot(from_rotation_arc_colinear(from, to) * from).abs()  1`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `from` or `to` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_x.documentation: Creates a quaternion from the `angle` (in radians) around the x axis.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_y.documentation: Creates a quaternion from the `angle` (in radians) around the y axis.

glam::DQuat::from_rotation_z.documentation: Creates a quaternion from the `angle` (in radians) around the z axis.

glam::DQuat::from_scaled_axis.documentation:
Create a quaternion that rotates `v.length()` radians around `v.normalize()`.
 `from_scaled_axis(Vec3::ZERO)` results in the identity quaternion.

glam::DQuat::from_vec4.documentation:
Creates a new rotation quaternion from a 4D vector.
 # Preconditions
 This function does not check if the input is normalized, it is up to the user to
 provide normalized input or to normalized the resulting quaternion.

glam::DQuat::from_xyzw.documentation:
Creates a new rotation quaternion.
 This should generally not be called manually unless you know what you are doing.
 Use one of the other constructors instead such as `identity` or `from_axis_angle`.
 `from_xyzw` is mostly used by unit tests and `serde` deserialization.
 # Preconditions
 This function does not check if the input is normalized, it is up to the user to
 provide normalized input or to normalized the resulting quaternion.

glam::DQuat::inverse.documentation:
Returns the inverse of a normalized quaternion.
 Typically quaternion inverse returns the conjugate of a normalized quaternion.
 Because `self` is assumed to already be unit length this method *does not* normalize
 before returning the conjugate.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DQuat::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` of length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of `1e-6`.

glam::DQuat::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::DQuat::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is generally faster than `length()` as it avoids a square
 root operation.

glam::DQuat::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on
 the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s`
 is `1.0`, the result will be equal to `rhs`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `end` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::mul.documentation:
Multiplies two quaternions. If they each represent a rotation, the result will
 represent the combined rotation.
 Note that due to floating point rounding the result may not be perfectly
 normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `rhs` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::mul_quat.documentation:
Multiplies two quaternions. If they each represent a rotation, the result will
 represent the combined rotation.
 Note that due to floating point rounding the result may not be perfectly normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `rhs` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::mul_vec3.documentation:
Multiplies a quaternion and a 3D vector, returning the rotated vector.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.
 Panics
 Will panic if `self` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::rotate_towards.documentation:
Rotates towards `rhs` up to `max_angle` (in radians).
 When `max_angle` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `max_angle` is equal to
 `self.angle_between(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. If `max_angle` is negative,
 rotates towards the exact opposite of `rhs`. Will not go past the target.
 Both quaternions must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `rhs` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::slerp.documentation:
Performs a spherical linear interpolation between `self` and `end`
 based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s`
 is `1.0`, the result will be equal to `end`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `end` are not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DQuat::sub.documentation:
Subtracts the `rhs` quaternion from `self`.
 The difference is not guaranteed to be normalized.

glam::DQuat::to_euler.documentation: Returns the rotation angles for the given euler rotation sequence.

glam::DQuat::to_scaled_axis.documentation: Returns the rotation axis scaled by the rotation in radians.

glam::DQuat::xyz.documentation: Returns the vector part of the quaternion.

glam::DVec2::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::DVec2::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DVec2::angle_to.documentation:
Returns the angle of rotation (in radians) from `self` to `rhs` in the range `[-, +]`.
 The inputs do not need to be unit vectors however they must be non-zero.

glam::DVec2::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::DVec2::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`f64::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::clamp_length.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min` and no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max`, or if either `min` or `max` is negative, when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::clamp_length_max.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `max` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::clamp_length_min.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec2::copysign.documentation: Returns a vector with signs of `rhs` and the magnitudes of `self`.

glam::DVec2::distance.documentation: Computes the Euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::DVec2::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::DVec2::div_euclid.documentation: Returns the element-wise quotient of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.

glam::DVec2::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::DVec2::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::DVec2::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::DVec2::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::DVec2::exp.documentation:
Returns a vector containing `e^self` (the exponential function) for each element of
 `self`.

glam::DVec2::extend.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` and the given `z` value.

glam::DVec2::floor.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the largest integer less than or equal to a number for each
 element of `self`.

glam::DVec2::fract.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this differs from the GLSL implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::DVec2::fract_gl.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this differs from the Rust implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::DVec2::from_angle.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector containing `[angle.cos(), angle.sin()]`. This can be used in
 conjunction with the [`rotate()`][Self::rotate()] method, e.g.
 `DVec2::from_angle(PI).rotate(DVec2::Y)` will create the vector `[-1, 0]`
 and rotate [`DVec2::Y`] around it returning `-DVec2::Y`.

glam::DVec2::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::DVec2::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.  If any element is either
 `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DVec2::is_finite_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_finite` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_finite(), y.is_finite(), ...]`.

glam::DVec2::is_nan_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_nan` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_nan(), y.is_nan(), ...]`.

glam::DVec2::is_negative_bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 2 bits set to the sign bits from the elements of `self`.
 A negative element results in a `1` bit and a positive element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.

glam::DVec2::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` is length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of approximately `1e-4`.

glam::DVec2::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::DVec2::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is faster than `length()` as it avoids a square root operation.

glam::DVec2::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::DVec2::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.max(rhs.x), self.y.max(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::DVec2::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.

glam::DVec2::midpoint.documentation:
Calculates the midpoint between `self` and `rhs`.
 The midpoint is the average of, or halfway point between, two vectors.
 `a.midpoint(b)` should yield the same result as `a.lerp(b, 0.5)`
 while being slightly cheaper to compute.

glam::DVec2::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.min(rhs.x), self.y.min(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::DVec2::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.

glam::DVec2::move_towards.documentation:
Moves towards `rhs` based on the value `d`.
 When `d` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `d` is equal to
 `self.distance(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. Will not go past `rhs`.

glam::DVec2::mul_add.documentation:
Fused multiply-add. Computes `(self * a) + b` element-wise with only one rounding
 error, yielding a more accurate result than an unfused multiply-add.
 Using `mul_add` *may* be more performant than an unfused multiply-add if the target
 architecture has a dedicated fma CPU instruction. However, this is not always true,
 and will be heavily dependant on designing algorithms with specific target hardware in
 mind.

glam::DVec2::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::DVec2::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::DVec2::perp.documentation: Returns a vector that is equal to `self` rotated by 90 degrees.

glam::DVec2::perp_dot.documentation:
The perpendicular dot product of `self` and `rhs`.
 Also known as the wedge product, 2D cross product, and determinant.

glam::DVec2::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::DVec2::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::DVec2::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec2::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f64::rem_euclid

glam::DVec2::rotate.documentation:
Returns `rhs` rotated by the angle of `self`. If `self` is normalized,
 then this just rotation. This is what you usually want. Otherwise,
 it will be like a rotation with a multiplication by `self`'s length.

glam::DVec2::rotate_towards.documentation:
Rotates towards `rhs` up to `max_angle` (in radians).
 When `max_angle` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `max_angle` is equal to
 `self.angle_between(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. If `max_angle` is negative,
 rotates towards the exact opposite of `rhs`. Will not go past the target.

glam::DVec2::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::DVec2::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::DVec2::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::DVec2::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::DVec2::to_angle.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) of this vector in the range `[-, +]`.
 The input does not need to be a unit vector however it must be non-zero.

glam::DVec2::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::DVec2::with_x.documentation: Creates a 2D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::DVec2::with_y.documentation: Creates a 2D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::DVec3::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::DVec3::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DVec3::angle_between.documentation:
Returns the angle (in radians) between two vectors in the range `[0, +]`.
 The inputs do not need to be unit vectors however they must be non-zero.

glam::DVec3::any_orthogonal_vector.documentation:
Returns some vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be finite and non-zero.
 The output vector is not necessarily unit length. For that use
 [`Self::any_orthonormal_vector()`] instead.

glam::DVec3::any_orthonormal_vector.documentation:
Returns any unit vector that is orthogonal to the given one.
 The input vector must be unit length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::DVec3::clamp.documentation:
Component-wise clamping of values, similar to [`f64::clamp`].
 Each element in `min` must be less-or-equal to the corresponding element in `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::clamp_length.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min` and no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max`, or if either `min` or `max` is negative, when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::clamp_length_max.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `max` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::clamp_length_min.documentation:
Returns a vector with a length no less than `min`.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `min` is negative when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::cmpeq.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `==` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words, this computes `[self.x == rhs.x, self.y == rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::cmpge.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x >= rhs.x, self.y >= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::cmpgt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `>` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x > rhs.x, self.y > rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::cmple.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x <= rhs.x, self.y <= rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::cmplt.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `<` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x < rhs.x, self.y < rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::cmpne.documentation:
Returns a vector mask containing the result of a `!=` comparison for each element of
 `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x != rhs.x, self.y != rhs.y, ..]` for all
 elements.

glam::DVec3::copysign.documentation: Returns a vector with signs of `rhs` and the magnitudes of `self`.

glam::DVec3::cross.documentation: Computes the cross product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::DVec3::distance.documentation: Computes the Euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::DVec3::distance_squared.documentation: Compute the squared euclidean distance between two points in space.

glam::DVec3::div_euclid.documentation: Returns the element-wise quotient of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.

glam::DVec3::dot.documentation: Computes the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::DVec3::dot_into_vec.documentation: Returns a vector where every component is the dot product of `self` and `rhs`.

glam::DVec3::element_product.documentation:
Returns the product of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x * self.y * ..`.

glam::DVec3::element_sum.documentation:
Returns the sum of all elements of `self`.
 In other words, this computes `self.x + self.y + ..`.

glam::DVec3::exp.documentation:
Returns a vector containing `e^self` (the exponential function) for each element of
 `self`.

glam::DVec3::extend.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` and the given `w` value.

glam::DVec3::floor.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the largest integer less than or equal to a number for each
 element of `self`.

glam::DVec3::fract.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this differs from the GLSL implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::DVec3::fract_gl.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the fractional part of the vector as `self - self.floor()`.
 Note that this differs from the Rust implementation of `fract` which returns
 `self - self.trunc()`.
 Note that this is fast but not precise for large numbers.

glam::DVec3::from_array.documentation: Creates a new vector from an array.

glam::DVec3::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.  If any element is either
 `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::DVec3::is_finite_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_finite` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_finite(), y.is_finite(), ...]`.

glam::DVec3::is_nan_mask.documentation:
Performs `is_nan` on each element of self, returning a vector mask of the results.
 In other words, this computes `[x.is_nan(), y.is_nan(), ...]`.

glam::DVec3::is_negative_bitmask.documentation:
Returns a bitmask with the lowest 3 bits set to the sign bits from the elements of `self`.
 A negative element results in a `1` bit and a positive element in a `0` bit.  Element `x` goes
 into the first lowest bit, element `y` into the second, etc.

glam::DVec3::is_normalized.documentation:
Returns whether `self` is length `1.0` or not.
 Uses a precision threshold of approximately `1e-4`.

glam::DVec3::length_recip.documentation:
Computes `1.0 / length()`.
 For valid results, `self` must _not_ be of length zero.

glam::DVec3::length_squared.documentation:
Computes the squared length of `self`.
 This is faster than `length()` as it avoids a square root operation.

glam::DVec3::lerp.documentation:
Performs a linear interpolation between `self` and `rhs` based on the value `s`.
 When `s` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`.  When `s` is `1.0`, the result
 will be equal to `rhs`. When `s` is outside of range `[0, 1]`, the result is linearly
 extrapolated.

glam::DVec3::max.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the maximum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.max(rhs.x), self.y.max(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::DVec3::max_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal maximum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `max(x, y, ..)`.

glam::DVec3::midpoint.documentation:
Calculates the midpoint between `self` and `rhs`.
 The midpoint is the average of, or halfway point between, two vectors.
 `a.midpoint(b)` should yield the same result as `a.lerp(b, 0.5)`
 while being slightly cheaper to compute.

glam::DVec3::min.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the minimum values for each element of `self` and `rhs`.
 In other words this computes `[self.x.min(rhs.x), self.y.min(rhs.y), ..]`.

glam::DVec3::min_element.documentation:
Returns the horizontal minimum of `self`.
 In other words this computes `min(x, y, ..)`.

glam::DVec3::move_towards.documentation:
Moves towards `rhs` based on the value `d`.
 When `d` is `0.0`, the result will be equal to `self`. When `d` is equal to
 `self.distance(rhs)`, the result will be equal to `rhs`. Will not go past `rhs`.

glam::DVec3::mul_add.documentation:
Fused multiply-add. Computes `(self * a) + b` element-wise with only one rounding
 error, yielding a more accurate result than an unfused multiply-add.
 Using `mul_add` *may* be more performant than an unfused multiply-add if the target
 architecture has a dedicated fma CPU instruction. However, this is not always true,
 and will be heavily dependant on designing algorithms with specific target hardware in
 mind.

glam::DVec3::normalize.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0.
 For valid results, `self` must be finite and _not_ of length zero, nor very close to zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`] and [`Self::normalize_or_zero()`].
 Panics
 Will panic if the resulting normalized vector is not finite when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::normalize_or.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns a
 fallback value.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be the fallback value.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::DVec3::normalize_or_zero.documentation:
Returns `self` normalized to length 1.0 if possible, else returns zero.
 In particular, if the input is zero (or very close to zero), or non-finite,
 the result of this operation will be zero.
 See also [`Self::try_normalize()`].

glam::DVec3::powf.documentation: Returns a vector containing each element of `self` raised to the power of `n`.

glam::DVec3::project_onto.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is zero length when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::project_onto_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector projection of `self` onto `rhs`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::recip.documentation: Returns a vector containing the reciprocal `1.0/n` of each element of `self`.

glam::DVec3::reflect.documentation:
Returns the reflection vector for a given incident vector `self` and surface normal
 `normal`.
 `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::refract.documentation:
Returns the refraction direction for a given incident vector `self`, surface normal
 `normal` and ratio of indices of refraction, `eta`. When total internal reflection occurs,
 a zero vector will be returned.
 `self` and `normal` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `self` or `normal` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::reject_from.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be of non-zero length.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` has a length of zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::reject_from_normalized.documentation:
Returns the vector rejection of `self` from `rhs`.
 The vector rejection is the vector perpendicular to the projection of `self` onto
 `rhs`, in rhs words the result of `self - self.project_onto(rhs)`.
 `rhs` must be normalized.
 # Panics
 Will panic if `rhs` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::DVec3::rem_euclid.documentation:
Returns the element-wise remainder of [Euclidean division] of `self` by `rhs`.
 [Euclidean division]: f64::rem_euclid

glam::DVec3::round.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the nearest integer to a number for each element of `self`.
 Round half-way cases away from 0.0.

glam::DVec3::select.documentation:
Creates a vector from the elements in `if_true` and `if_false`, selecting which to use
 for each element of `self`.
 A true element in the mask uses the corresponding element from `if_true`, and false
 uses the element from `if_false`.

glam::DVec3::signum.documentation:
Returns a vector with elements representing the sign of `self`.
 - `1.0` if the number is positive, `+0.0` or `INFINITY`
 - `-1.0` if the number is negative, `-0.0` or `NEG_INFINITY`
 - `NAN` if the number is `NAN`

glam::DVec3::splat.documentation: Creates a vector with all elements set to `v`.

glam::DVec3::trunc.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the integer part each element of `self`. This means numbers are
 always truncated towards zero.

glam::DVec3::truncate.documentation:
Creates a 2D vector from the `x` and `y` elements of `self`, discarding `z`.
 Truncation may also be performed by using [`self.xy()`][crate::swizzles::Vec3Swizzles::xy()].

glam::DVec3::with_x.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `x`.

glam::DVec3::with_y.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `y`.

glam::DVec3::with_z.documentation: Creates a 3D vector from `self` with the given value of `z`.

glam::DVec4::abs.documentation: Returns a vector containing the absolute value of each element of `self`.

glam::DVec4::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs` is
 less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two vectors contain similar elements. It works best when
 comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used depends on
 the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::DVec4::ceil.documentation:
Returns a vector containing the smallest integer greater than or equal to a number for
 each element of `self`.

glam::DVec4::clamp.documentation:

 Will panic if `min` is greater than `max` when `glam_assert` is enabled.

Returns a vector with a length no more than `max`.

glam::DVec4::clamp_length_min.documentation:

glam::DVec4::with_w.documentation: Creates a 4D vector from `self` with the given value of `w`.

glam::Mat2::abs.documentation: Takes the absolute value of each element in `self`

glam::Mat2::abs_diff_eq.documentation:
Returns true if the absolute difference of all elements between `self` and `rhs`
 is less than or equal to `max_abs_diff`.
 This can be used to compare if two matrices contain similar elements. It works best
 when comparing with a known value. The `max_abs_diff` that should be used used
 depends on the values being compared against.
 For more see
 [comparing floating point numbers](https://randomascii.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/comparing-floating-point-numbers-2012-edition/).

glam::Mat2::col.documentation:
Returns the matrix column for the given `index`.
 # Panics
 Panics if `index` is greater than 1.

glam::Mat2::div_scalar.documentation: Divides a 2x2 matrix by a scalar.

glam::Mat2::from_angle.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix containing a rotation of `angle` (in radians).

glam::Mat2::from_cols.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix from two column vectors.

glam::Mat2::from_diagonal.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix with its diagonal set to `diagonal` and all other entries set to 0.

glam::Mat2::from_mat3.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix from a 3x3 matrix, discarding the 2nd row and column.

glam::Mat2::from_mat3_minor.documentation:

 and `j`th row.
 # Panics
 Panics if `i` or `j` is greater than 2.

glam::Mat2::from_mat3a.documentation: Creates a 2x2 matrix from a 3x3 matrix, discarding the 2nd row and column.

glam::Mat2::from_scale_angle.documentation:

glam::Mat2::inverse.documentation:

 # Panics
 Will panic if the determinant of `self` is zero when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Mat2::is_finite.documentation:
Returns `true` if, and only if, all elements are finite.
 If any element is either `NaN`, positive or negative infinity, this will return `false`.

glam::Mat2::mul_scalar.documentation: Multiplies a 2x2 matrix by a scalar.

glam::Mat2::row.documentation:

 # Panics

glam::Mat2::to_cols_array_2d.documentation:
Creates a `[[f32; 2]; 2]` 2D array storing data in column major order.

 radians).

 [`Self::transform_point2()`] and [`Self::transform_vector2()`].

 radians).
 # Panics
 Will panic if `axis` is not normalized when `glam_assert` is enabled.

glam::Mat3::from_mat4.documentation: Creates a 3x3 matrix from a 4x4 matrix, discarding the 4th row and column.
